As Josep Borrell was just elected President of the European
Parliament, it is worth recalling and publicising his stated position
on software patentability. This position was expressed between the 
[[Cons040518En| Council vote of 18 May 2004]]
and the 
[[ElectResu0406En| European elections]].  

Summary: the socialist and
Spanish governement's position is clear that restrictions to the
patentability of computer-implemented inventions are needed
(maintaining software outside the scope of patentable subject matter)
and that copyright was enough to ensure the dynamics of software
innovation.  

